WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:04.550
okay thank you everyone for being here and thanks everyone for helping

00:00:04.550 --> 00:00:08.210
to organize this event my name is jonathan warden i

00:00:08.210 --> 00:00:12.800
'm an independent researcher i am an engineer co-founder of

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:16.190
a small research organization called social protocols.

00:00:16.190 --> 00:00:19.750
org my focus is on the the problem of how the design

00:00:19.770 --> 00:00:25.680
of platforms social platforms and algorithms has positive or negative social outcomes

00:00:25.750 --> 00:00:32.360
and my big thesis is that if platforms can inadvertently create

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:37.020
all these negative social outcomes couldn't they be intentionally designed to

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:42.270
produce positive social outcomes so instead of misinformation and toxicity and division

00:00:42.270 --> 00:00:47.120
couldn't they promote intelligent conversation and finding common ground i've

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:51.590
been approaching this problem from the point of view of game theory

00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:58.030
information theory argumentation theory collective intelligence a whole lot of theory

00:00:58.140 --> 00:01:01.300
and the reason i'm working on community notes now is it

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:06.880
's one of the only examples i know of where the theory

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:12.600
has been put into practice successfully and at scale community notes on

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:17.220
twitter has actually helped to decrease the the spread of misinformation on

00:01:17.280 --> 00:01:23.500
twitter so i'm going to talk to you briefly about why

00:01:23.500 --> 00:01:28.170
i think community notes is great both for fighting misinformation and as

00:01:28.170 --> 00:01:32.490
a unique and powerful scalable tool for peer moderation i'll give

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:35.930
you a brief demonstration of blue notes and then i'll talk

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:41.280
mainly about the architecture some of the architectural challenges with bringing community

00:01:41.280 --> 00:01:46.120
notes to at protocol and making it decentralized and composable some

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:52.910
of the challenges include making annotations work via labeler infrastructure

00:01:52.910 --> 00:01:58.540
privacy and anonymity and of course bots and manipulation so 300

00:01:58.650 --> 00:02:03.420
years ago jonathan swift said falsehood flies and truth comes

00:02:03.430 --> 00:02:07.280
limping after it so that when men come to be unde

00:02:07.280 --> 00:02:10.240
ceived it is too late and he hadn't even heard

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:16.730
of twitter he um rumors have always in misinformation or falsehood

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:21.790
has always spread and it spreads largely because people think that it

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:25.730
's true some people are spreading misinformation maliciously but it spreads

00:02:25.730 --> 00:02:30.350
faster because people don't know the truth so what what community

00:02:30.360 --> 00:02:34.960
notes does is it helps increase the velocity of truth in social

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:38.620
networks it helps the truth sometimes catch up to people and so

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:43.010
people you know where normally they just share something because they believe

00:02:43.010 --> 00:02:45.360
that it's true it looks plausible they kind of want to

00:02:45.360 --> 00:02:48.250
believe it's true somebody just tells them hey this is actually

00:02:48.250 --> 00:02:51.400
not true this is just a rumor this image is fake well

00:02:51.400 --> 00:02:58.070
then maybe they wouldn't share it now besides being a great

00:02:58.070 --> 00:03:04.280
tool for for combating misinformation community notes also is a very

00:03:04.290 --> 00:03:09.520
unique and powerful peer moderation protocol it is decentralized in the sense

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:13.820
that there are no privileged roles there are no administrators there are

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:18.260
no editors there's just the community and so it is moderation

00:03:18.260 --> 00:03:24.210
without moderators and and that means that instead of trusting fact

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:30.960
checkers or editors instead of trusting people or in or organizations

00:03:30.970 --> 00:03:34.750
you place your trust in the community and in the protocol that

00:03:34.760 --> 00:03:40.390
that community uses to make decisions and there are some benefits in

00:03:40.390 --> 00:03:44.560
placing trust in the community one is that people trust the results

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:48.430
of moderation decisions more that way people have a lot of trust

00:03:48.430 --> 00:03:52.740
in community notes a plot across the political spectrum and one of

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:57.200
the reasons for that is that it's perceived as being fairly

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:02.140
neutral community notes was developed before Elon Musk took over and it

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:06.080
's still the algorithm is open source all the data is open

00:04:06.090 --> 00:04:08.940
and it's still running using that same the same algorithm and

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.220
for the most part people still trust community notes even though they

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:15.440
don't trust necessarily the person that's running it and people

00:04:15.450 --> 00:04:18.800
perceive it as neutral because in a sense it really is neutral

00:04:18.800 --> 00:04:24.660
it is not just a naive majority voting based crowd-s

00:04:24.660 --> 00:04:28.410
ourced fact-checking system it uses a very innovative

00:04:28.420 --> 00:04:31.790
bridging algorithm what this algorithm tries to do it's not

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:34.660
just trying to find what's people think or what's most

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:38.740
popular it tries to find common ground and so one way of

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:43.600
looking at that is you can think of the algorithm as looking

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.710
at people's votes and saying okay well these votes this person

00:04:46.710 --> 00:04:49.270
's upvoted this because they have a left-wing

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:51.560
bias and this person all these upvotes because this person

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:54.230
has a right-wing bias and maybe this person just up

00:04:54.230 --> 00:04:56.800
votes everything or just downvotes everything so they just

00:04:56.830 --> 00:05:00.510
have this this upvote bias but these votes there are

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:05.080
some votes can that cannot be explained away by bias and so

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:09.850
this this model uses discovers these latent factors that influence people's

00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:13.710
votes and it says look this latent factor represents an area of

00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:18.160
common ground and when a post or a community note has this

00:05:18.250 --> 00:05:22.040
factor people are more likely to upvote that post or

00:05:22.050 --> 00:05:26.870
that community note across the political spectrum across the spectrum of opinion

00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:32.310
so in a sense it extracts signal from noise if you

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:39.570
have for example a group where the majority of people voting on

00:05:39.570 --> 00:05:44.000
community notes is right-wing which is actually what happened with

00:05:44.010 --> 00:05:47.780
what exists in x right now if a community note gets a

